<span id="v.iv.v.viii-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="v.iv.v.viii-p1.1"></span>Chapter 8.—</span>11.  Likewise Felix of
Buslacene said:  "In admitting heretics without the baptism of the
Church, let no one prefer custom to reason and truth; because reason and
truth always prevail to the exclusion of custom." <span
id="fr_1276"></span>[1277](#fn_1276.md)   Nothing could be better, if it be
reason, and if it be truth; but this we shall see presently.  Meanwhile,
it is clear from the words of this man also that the custom was the
other way.

